European stocks opened higher and U.S. futures advanced Thursday on signs of potential progress in Washington toward a fresh fiscal stimulus package. Novartis AG and other healthcare companies lead shares higher in Europe as traders awaited purchasing managers’ data from Germany and other key economies. U.S. equity indexes were supported by speculation that bargaining positions narrowed about more assistance, with Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin reportedly bolstering the level previously offered by his party’s negotiators. The dollar fell on Thursday just after ending its worst quarter in more than three years. In Japan, the Tokyo Stock Exchange halted trading after its worst breakdown, exacerbating an already slow day for stock markets in Asia where China, Hong Kong, Taiwan and South Korea are closed for holidays. Treasury yields edged higher. “We’re looking at a volatile October coming into the elections,” Mariann Montagne, portfolio manager at Gradient Investments LLC, said on Bloomberg TV. “The dollar will continue to pull back a bit, and that’s a function of the volatility here, the relative growth here versus abroad.” Mnuchin said he and Nancy Pelosi “made a lot of progress in a lot of areas,” and the House speaker said talks with the Treasury secretary will continue. Senate Majority Leader Mitch McConnell was pessimistic, saying the two sides remain “far apart” on the amount of spending. The Democrats will nevertheless vote on their $2.2 billion proposal later in the day, although it has no chance in the Senate. President Donald Trump signed a stopgap funding bill, preventing a partial federal government shutdown. U.S. Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin says he and House Speaker Nancy Pelosi are getting closer to a deal on the next virus relief package. Source: Bloomberg Here are some key events coming up: These are the main moves in markets: